snippet.textDisplay:
I disagree with your take on them having to stick to existing force powers. They added stuff to the force with each Star Wars movie from the beginning, but since it was George Lucas it was just accepted. In Star Wars '77 no Jedi we're jumping 15 feet in the air and lightsaber battles sucked. They changed that in the prequal trilogy. Also why is it acceptable to be able to use the force to choke people, lift people, throw people, lift inanimate objects and jump higher, but you can't propel yourself forward in frictionless space? I had a lot of plotline issues with RoS, it wasn't a perfect film, but it's nowhere near as bad as old fanboys are making it out to be. 

20 years from now people watching 1-9 for the first time aren't going to be crapping their pants saying "Nuh uh, they couldn't do that in the last movie!" They're just going to watch it and think about how annoying Jar Jar is, how the whole "Anakin being the chosen one" for 1-6 was pointless because they brought back Palpatine anyway and how 7-9 doesn't feel like a cohesive trilogy. There are bigger issues with these films than force powers. 

Maclunkey!
